# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: category-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] In mathematics, a **category** (sometimes called an **abstract category** to distinguish it from a concrete category) is a collection of "objects" that are linked by "arrows".
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] A category has two basic properties: the ability to compose the arrows associatively and the existence of an identity arrow for each object.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] A simple example is the category of sets, whose objects are sets and whose arrows are functions.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Category theory is a branch of mathematics that seeks to generalize all of mathematics in terms of categories, independent of what their objects and arrows represent.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Virtually every branch of modern mathematics can be described in terms of categories, and doing so often reveals deep insights and similarities between seemingly different areas of mathematics.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] As such, category theory provides an alternative foundation for mathematics to set theory and other proposed axiomatic foundations.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] In general, the objects and arrows may be abstract entities of any kind, and the notion of category provides a fundamental and abstract way to describe mathematical entities and their relationships.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] In addition to formalizing mathematics, category theory is also used to formalize many other systems in computer science, such as the semantics of programming languages.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Two categories are the same if they have the same collection of objects, the same collection of arrows, and the same associative method of composing any pair of arrows.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Two *different* categories may also be considered "equivalent" for purposes of category theory, even if they do not have precisely the same structure.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] A mapping between two categories compatible with their respective structures is called a functor.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Well-known categories are denoted by a short capitalized word or abbreviation in bold or italics: examples include **Set**, the category of sets and set functions; **Ring**, the category of rings and ring homomorphisms; and **Top**, the category of topological spaces and continuous maps.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] All of the preceding categories have the identity map as identity arrows and composition as the associative operation on arrows.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Any monoid can be understood as a special sort of category (with a single object whose self-morphisms are represented by the elements of the monoid), and so can any preorder.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] The classic and still much used text on category theory is *Categories for the Working Mathematician* by Saunders Mac Lane.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Other references are given in the References below.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] The basic definitions in this article are contained within the first few chapters of any of these books.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] There are many equivalent definitions of a category.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] One commonly used definition is as follows.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] We write $f:a\to b$ , and we say " f is a morphism from a to b ".
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] We write $\operatorname {hom} (a,b)$ (or $\operatorname {hom} _{\mathcal {C}}(a,b)$ when there may be confusion about to which category $\operatorname {hom} (a,b)$ refers) to denote the **hom-class** of all morphisms from a to b .
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Some authors write the composite of morphisms in "diagrammatic order", writing $f\,;g$ (sometimes with ⨟ ) or $fg$ instead of $g\circ f$ .
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] From these axioms, one can prove that there is exactly one identity morphism for every object.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Often the map assigning each object its identity morphism is treated as an extra part of the structure of a category, namely a class function $i:\operatorname {ob} ({\mathcal {C}})\to \operatorname {mor} ({\mathcal {C}})$ .
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Some authors use a slight variant of the definition in which each object is identified with the corresponding identity morphism.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] This stems from the idea that the fundamental data of categories are morphisms and not objects.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] In fact, categories can be defined without reference to objects at all using a partial binary operation with additional properties.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] A category ${\mathcal {C}}$ is called **small** if both $\operatorname {ob} ({\mathcal {C}})$ and $\operatorname {mor} ({\mathcal {C}})$ are actually sets and not proper classes, and **large** otherwise.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] A **locally small category** is a category such that for all objects a and b , the hom-class $\operatorname {hom} (a,b)$ is a set, called a **homset**.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Many important categories in mathematics (such as the category of sets), although not small, are at least locally small.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Since, in small categories, the objects form a set, a small category can be viewed as an algebraic structure similar to a monoid but without requiring closure properties.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Large categories on the other hand can be used to create "structures" of algebraic structures.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] The class of all sets (as objects) together with all functions between them (as morphisms), where the composition of morphisms is the usual function composition, forms a large category, **Set**.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] It is the most basic and the most commonly used category in mathematics.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] The category **Rel** consists of all sets (as objects) with binary relations between them (as morphisms).
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Abstracting from relations instead of functions yields allegories, a special class of categories.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Any class can be viewed as a category whose only morphisms are the identity morphisms.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] For any given set I , the *discrete category on I* is the small category that has the elements of I as objects and only the identity morphisms as morphisms.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Any preordered set $(P,\leq )$ forms a small category, where the objects are the members of P , the morphisms are arrows pointing from x to y when $x\leq y$ .
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] The existence of identity morphisms and the composability of the morphisms are guaranteed by the reflexivity and the transitivity of the preorder.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] For any two objects, there is at most one morphism from one to the other (such a category is called thin), and if $\leq$ is in addition antisymmetric, there can be at most one morphism between any two objects.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] In particular, any partially ordered set and any equivalence relation can be seen as a small category.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Any ordinal number can be seen as a category when viewed as an ordered set.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Any monoid (any algebraic structure with a single associative binary operation and an identity element) forms a small category with a single object x .
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] (Here, x is any fixed set.) The morphisms from x to x are precisely the elements of the monoid, the identity morphism of x is the identity of the monoid, and the categorical composition of morphisms is given by the monoid operation.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Several definitions and theorems about monoids may be generalized for categories.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Similarly any group can be seen as a category with a single object in which every morphism is *invertible*, that is, for every morphism f there is a morphism g that is both left and right inverse to f under composition.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] A morphism that is invertible in this sense is called an isomorphism.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] A groupoid is a category in which every morphism is an isomorphism.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Groupoids are generalizations of groups, group actions and equivalence relations.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] From the point of view of category theory, a group is just a groupoid with exactly one object.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] In the language of category theory, this means here two morphisms may not have the same source object (or target object, because in this case for any morphism the source object and the target object are same: the base point) so they cannot compose with each other.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Any directed graph (or, more generally, a quiver) generates a small category: the objects are the vertices of the graph, and the morphisms are the paths in the graph (augmented with loops as needed) where composition of morphisms is concatenation of paths.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Such a category is called the *free category* generated by the graph.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] The class of all preordered sets with order-preserving functions (i.e., monotone-increasing functions) as morphisms forms a category, **Ord**.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] It is a concrete category, i.e. a category whose objects can be identified with sets with some type of additional structure, while the morphisms are functions that respect this structure.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] The class of all groups with group homomorphisms as morphisms and function composition as the composition operation forms a large category, **Grp**.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Like $\mathbf {Ord}$ , $\mathbf {Grp}$ is a concrete category.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] The category **Ab**, consisting of all abelian groups and their group homomorphisms, is a full subcategory of $\mathbf {Grp}$ , and the prototype of an abelian category.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] The class of all graphs forms another concrete category, where morphisms are graph homomorphisms (i.e., mappings between graphs which send vertices to vertices and edges to edges in a way that preserves all adjacency and incidence relations).
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Examples of concrete categories are given by the following table.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Fiber bundles with bundle maps between them form a concrete category.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] The category **Cat** consists of all small categories, with functors between them as morphisms.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] In turn, a functor category has as objects functors between two fixed categories and as morphisms natural transformations between them.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Any category ${\mathcal {C}}$ can itself be considered as a new category in a different way: the objects are the same as those in the original category but the arrows are those of the original category reversed.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] This is called the *dual* or *opposite category* and is denoted ${\mathcal {C}}^{\mathrm {op} }$ .
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Such pairs can be composed componentwise.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] By identifying a collection of morphisms in ${\mathcal {C}}$ via a suitable equivalence relation $\sim$ , one can construct the *quotient category* ${\mathcal {C}}/\sim$ .
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] The dual notion is that of an *undercategory* or *coslice category*, and both are special cases of a construction called *comma category*.
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Given a class W of morphisms in ${\mathcal {C}}$ , the *localization* ${\mathcal {C}}[W^{-1}]$ turns the morphisms from W into isomorphisms (see below).
[src:category-theory/category-mathematics] Relations among morphisms (such as $fg=h$ ) can most conveniently be represented with commutative diagrams, where the objects are represented as points and the morphisms as arrows.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Many areas of computer science also rely on category theory, such as functional programming and semantics.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] A category is formed by two sorts of objects: the objects of the category, and the morphisms, which relate two objects called the *source* and the *target* of the morphism.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] A morphism is often represented by an arrow from its source to its target (see the figure).
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Morphisms can be composed if the target of the first morphism equals the source of the second one.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Morphism composition has similar properties as function composition (associativity and existence of an identity morphism for each object).
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Morphisms are often some sort of functions, but this is not always the case.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] For example, a monoid may be viewed as a category with a single object, whose morphisms are the elements of the monoid.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] A third fundamental concept is a natural transformation that may be viewed as a morphism of functors.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] A prototypical example of a category is **Set**, the category of sets and functions between them.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] The objects of **Set** are just sets, and a morphism from a set *X* to a set *Y* is a function *f* : *X* → *Y*.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] The category axioms are satisfied since every set has an identity function, and since composition of functions is associative.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Relations among morphisms (such as *fg* = *h*) are often depicted using commutative diagrams, with "points" (corners) representing objects and "arrows" representing morphisms.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Morphisms can have any of the following properties.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Every retraction is an epimorphism, and every section is a monomorphism.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Functors are structure-preserving maps between categories.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] They can be thought of as morphisms in the category of all (small) categories.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] A **contravariant** functor *F*: *C* → *D* is like a covariant functor, except that it "turns morphisms around" ("reverses all the arrows").
[src:category-theory/category-theory] More specifically, every morphism *f* : *x* → *y* in *C* must be assigned to a morphism *F*(*f*) : *F*(*y*) → *F*(*x*) in *D*.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] In other words, a contravariant functor acts as a covariant functor from the opposite category *C*op to *D*.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] A *natural transformation* is a relation between two functors.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Functors often describe "natural constructions" and natural transformations then describe "natural homomorphisms" between two such constructions.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Sometimes two quite different constructions yield "the same" result; this is expressed by a natural isomorphism between the two functors.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] The two functors *F* and *G* are called *naturally isomorphic* if there exists a natural transformation from *F* to *G* such that *η**X* is an isomorphism for every object *X* in *C*.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Using the language of category theory, many areas of mathematical study can be categorized.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Categories include sets, groups and topologies.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Hence, the challenge is to define special objects without referring to the internal structure of those objects.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] To define the empty set without referring to elements, or the product topology without referring to open sets, one can characterize these objects in terms of their relations to other objects, as given by the morphisms of the respective categories.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Thus, the task is to find *universal properties* that uniquely determine the objects of interest.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Numerous important constructions can be described in a purely categorical way if the *category limit* can be developed and dualized to yield the notion of a *colimit*.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] It is a natural question to ask: under which conditions can two categories be considered *essentially the same*, in the sense that theorems about one category can readily be transformed into theorems about the other category?
[src:category-theory/category-theory] The major tool one employs to describe such a situation is called *equivalence of categories*, which is given by appropriate functors between two categories.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Categorical equivalence has found numerous applications in mathematics.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] The definitions of categories and functors provide only the very basics of categorical algebra; additional important topics are listed below.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Although there are strong interrelations between all of these topics, the given order can be considered as a guideline for further reading.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Many of the above concepts, especially equivalence of categories, adjoint functor pairs, and functor categories, can be situated into the context of *higher-dimensional categories*.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Briefly, if we consider a morphism between two objects as a "process taking us from one object to another", then higher-dimensional categories allow us to profitably generalize this by considering "higher-dimensional processes".
[src:category-theory/category-theory] For example, a (strict) 2-category is a category together with "morphisms between morphisms", i.e., processes which allow us to transform one morphism into another.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] We can then "compose" these "bimorphisms" both horizontally and vertically, and we require a 2-dimensional "exchange law" to hold, relating the two composition laws.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] In this context, the standard example is **Cat**, the 2-category of all (small) categories, and in this example, bimorphisms of morphisms are simply natural transformations of morphisms in the usual sense.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Another basic example is to consider a 2-category with a single object; these are essentially monoidal categories.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Bicategories are a weaker notion of 2-dimensional categories in which the composition of morphisms is not strictly associative, but only associative "up to" an isomorphism.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] This process can be extended for all natural numbers *n*, and these are called *n*-categories.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] There is even a notion of *ω-category* corresponding to the ordinal number ω.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Higher-dimensional categories are part of the broader mathematical field of higher-dimensional algebra, a concept introduced by Ronald Brown.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] For a conversational introduction to these ideas, see John Baez, 'A Tale of *n*-categories' (1996).
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Their work was an important part of the transition from intuitive and geometric homology to homological algebra.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Eilenberg and Mac Lane later wrote that their goal was to understand natural transformations, which first required the definition of functors, then categories.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Stanisław Ulam, and some writing on his behalf, have claimed that related ideas were current in the late 1930s in Poland.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Eilenberg was Polish, and studied mathematics in Poland in the 1930s.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Category theory is also, in some sense, a continuation of the work of Emmy Noether (one of Mac Lane's teachers) in formalizing abstract processes; Noether realized that understanding a type of mathematical structure requires understanding the processes that preserve that structure (homomorphisms).
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Eilenberg and Mac Lane introduced categories for understanding and formalizing the processes (functors) that relate topological structures to algebraic structures (topological invariants) that characterize them.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Category theory was originally introduced for the need of homological algebra, and widely extended for the need of modern algebraic geometry (scheme theory).
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Category theory may be viewed as an extension of universal algebra, as the latter studies algebraic structures, and the former applies to any kind of mathematical structure and studies also the relationships between structures of different nature.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] For this reason, it is used throughout mathematics.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Applications to mathematical logic and semantics (categorical abstract machine) came later.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Certain categories called topoi (singular *topos*) can even serve as an alternative to axiomatic set theory as a foundation of mathematics.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] A topos can also be considered as a specific type of category with two additional topos axioms.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] These foundational applications of category theory have been worked out in fair detail as a basis for, and justification of, constructive mathematics.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Topos theory is a form of abstract sheaf theory, with geometric origins, and leads to ideas such as pointless topology.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Categorical logic is now a well-defined field based on type theory for intuitionistic logics, with applications in functional programming and domain theory, where a cartesian closed category is taken as a non-syntactic description of a lambda calculus.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] At the very least, category theoretic language clarifies what exactly these related areas have in common (in some abstract sense).
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Category theory has been applied in other fields as well, see applied category theory.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] For example, John Baez has shown a link between Feynman diagrams in physics and monoidal categories.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] Another application of category theory, more specifically topos theory, has been made in mathematical music theory, see for example the book *The Topos of Music, Geometric Logic of Concepts, Theory, and Performance* by Guerino Mazzola.
[src:category-theory/category-theory] More recent efforts to introduce undergraduates to categories as a foundation for mathematics include those of Lawvere & Rosebrugh (2003), and Lawvere and Stephen Schanuel (1997).
[src:category-theory/functor] In mathematics, specifically category theory, a **functor** is a mapping between categories.
[src:category-theory/functor] Functors were first considered in algebraic topology, where algebraic objects (such as the fundamental group) are associated to topological spaces, and maps between these algebraic objects are associated to continuous maps between spaces.
[src:category-theory/functor] Nowadays, functors are used throughout modern mathematics to relate various categories.
[src:category-theory/functor] Thus, functors are important in every area of mathematics where category theory is applied.
[src:category-theory/functor] The words *category* and *functor* were borrowed by mathematicians from the philosophers Aristotle and Rudolf Carnap, respectively.
[src:category-theory/functor] The latter used *functor* in a linguistic context; see function word.
[src:category-theory/functor] That is, functors must preserve identity morphisms and composition of morphisms.
[src:category-theory/functor] There are many constructions in mathematics that would be functors but for the fact that they "turn morphisms around" and "reverse composition".
[src:category-theory/functor] Note that contravariant functors reverse the direction of composition.
[src:category-theory/functor] Ordinary functors are also called **covariant functors** in order to distinguish them from contravariant ones.
[src:category-theory/functor] Note that one can also define a contravariant functor as a *covariant* functor on the opposite category $C^{\mathrm {op} }$ .
[src:category-theory/functor] Some authors prefer to write all expressions covariantly.
[src:category-theory/functor] That is, instead of saying $F\colon C\to D$ is a contravariant functor, they simply write $F\colon C^{\mathrm {op} }\to D$ (or sometimes $F\colon C\to D^{\mathrm {op} }$ ) and call it a functor.
[src:category-theory/functor] Contravariant functors are also occasionally called *cofunctors*.
[src:category-theory/functor] This terminology is contrary to the one used in category theory because it is the covectors that have *pullbacks* in general and are thus *contravariant*, whereas vectors in general are *covariant* since they can be *pushed forward*.
[src:category-theory/functor] See also Covariance and contravariance of vectors.
[src:category-theory/functor] Every functor $F\colon C\to D$ induces the **opposite functor** $F^{\mathrm {op} }\colon C^{\mathrm {op} }\to D^{\mathrm {op} }$ , where $C^{\mathrm {op} }$ and $D^{\mathrm {op} }$ are the opposite categories to C and D .
[src:category-theory/functor] By definition, $F^{\mathrm {op} }$ maps objects and morphisms in the identical way as does F .
[src:category-theory/functor] Since $C^{\mathrm {op} }$ does not coincide with C as a category, and similarly for D , $F^{\mathrm {op} }$ is distinguished from F .
[src:category-theory/functor] Note that, following the property of opposite category, $\left(F^{\mathrm {op} }\right)^{\mathrm {op} }=F$ .
[src:category-theory/functor] A **bifunctor** (also known as a **binary functor**) is a functor whose domain is a product category.
[src:category-theory/functor] For example, the Hom functor is of the type *Cop* × *C* → **Set**.
[src:category-theory/functor] It can be seen as a functor in *two* arguments; it is contravariant in one argument, covariant in the other.
[src:category-theory/functor] A **multifunctor** is a generalization of the functor concept to *n* variables.
[src:category-theory/functor] So, for example, a bifunctor is a multifunctor with *n* = 2.
[src:category-theory/functor] One can compose functors, i.e. if *F* is a functor from *A* to *B* and *G* is a functor from *B* to *C* then one can form the composite functor *G* ∘ *F* from *A* to *C*.
[src:category-theory/functor] Composition of functors is associative where defined.
[src:category-theory/functor] Identity of composition of functors is the identity functor.
[src:category-theory/functor] This shows that functors can be considered as morphisms in categories of categories, for example in the category of small categories.
[src:category-theory/functor] A small category with a single object is the same thing as a monoid: the morphisms of a one-object category can be thought of as elements of the monoid, and composition in the category is thought of as the monoid operation.
[src:category-theory/functor] Functors between one-object categories correspond to monoid homomorphisms.
[src:category-theory/functor] So in a sense, functors between arbitrary categories are a kind of generalization of monoid homomorphisms to categories with more than one object.
[src:category-theory/functor] , maps an object to itself and a morphism to itself.
[src:category-theory/functor] Similar remarks apply to the colimit functor (which assigns to every functor its colimit, and is covariant).
[src:category-theory/functor] , i.e. topological spaces with distinguished points.
[src:category-theory/functor] , with the group operation of concatenation.
[src:category-theory/functor] In the category of topological spaces (without distinguished point), one considers homotopy classes of generic curves, but they cannot be composed unless they share an endpoint.
[src:category-theory/functor] instead of the fundamental group, and this construction is functorial.
[src:category-theory/functor] ) of all real-valued continuous functions on that space.
[src:category-theory/functor] , a covariant functor from the category of pointed differentiable manifolds to the category of real vector spaces.
[src:category-theory/functor] is a group, then this action is a group homomorphism.
[src:category-theory/functor] to its underlying function of sets is a functor.
[src:category-theory/functor] Going in the opposite direction of forgetful functors are free functors.
[src:category-theory/functor] Functions get mapped to group homomorphisms between free groups.
[src:category-theory/functor] Free constructions exist for many categories based on structured sets.
[src:category-theory/functor] An important goal in many settings is to determine whether a given functor is representable.
[src:category-theory/functor] The collection of all functors from *C* to *D* forms the objects of a category: the functor category.
[src:category-theory/functor] Morphisms in this category are natural transformations between functors.
[src:category-theory/functor] Functors are often defined by universal properties; examples are the tensor product, the direct sum and direct product of groups or vector spaces, construction of free groups and modules, direct and inverse limits.
[src:category-theory/functor] The concepts of limit and colimit generalize several of the above.
[src:category-theory/functor] Universal constructions often give rise to pairs of adjoint functors.
[src:category-theory/functor] Functors sometimes appear in functional programming.
[src:category-theory/functor] For instance, the programming language Haskell has a class `Functor` where `fmap` is a polytypic function used to map functions (*morphisms* on *Hask*, the category of Haskell types) between existing types to functions between some new types.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] In category theory, a branch of mathematics, a **monad** is a triple $(T,\eta ,\mu )$ consisting of a functor *T* from a category to itself and two natural transformations $\eta ,\mu$ that satisfy versions of the associativity and unitality axioms.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Equivalently, a monad is a monoid in the category of endofunctors of some fixed category (an endofunctor is a functor mapping a category to itself).
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] For example, if $F,G$ are functors adjoint to each other, then $T=G\circ F$ together with $\eta ,\mu$ determined by the adjoint relation is a monad.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] A monad as a tool for studying algebraic gadgets; for example, a group can be described by a certain monad.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Monads are used in the theory of pairs of adjoint functors, and they generalize closure operators on partially ordered sets to arbitrary categories.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Monads are also useful in the theory of datatypes, the denotational semantics of imperative programming languages, and in functional programming languages, allowing languages without mutable state to do things such as simulate for-loops; see Monad (functional programming).
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] A monad is also called, especially in old literature, a **triple**, **triad**, **standard construction** and **fundamental construction**.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] A monad is a certain type of endofunctor.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] For example, if F and G are a pair of adjoint functors, with F left adjoint to G , then the composition $G\circ F$ is a monad.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] If F and G are inverse to each other, the corresponding monad is the identity functor.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] In general, adjunctions are not equivalences—they relate categories of different natures.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The monad theory matters as part of the effort to capture what it is that adjunctions 'preserve'.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The other half of the theory, of what can be learned likewise from consideration of $F\circ G$ , is discussed under the dual theory of *comonads*.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Throughout this article, C denotes a category.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] A *monad* on C consists of an endofunctor $T\colon C\to C$ together with two natural transformations: $\eta \colon 1_{C}\to T$ (where $1_{C}$ denotes the identity functor on C ) and $\mu \colon T^{2}\to T$ (where $T^{2}$ is the functor $T\circ T$ from C to C ).
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The first axiom is akin to the associativity in monoids if we think of $\mu$ as the monoid's binary operation, and the second axiom is akin to the existence of an identity element (which we think of as given by $\eta$ ).
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Indeed, a monad on C can alternatively be defined as a monoid in the category $\mathbf {End} _{C}$ whose objects are the endofunctors of C and whose morphisms are the natural transformations between them, with the monoidal structure induced by the composition of endofunctors.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The *power set monad* is a monad ${\mathcal {P}}$ on the category $\mathbf {Set}$ : For a set A let $T(A)$ be the power set of A and for a function $f\colon A\to B$ let $T(f)$ be the function between the power sets induced by taking direct images under f .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] For every set A , we have a map $\eta _{A}\colon A\to T(A)$ , which assigns to every $a\in A$ the singleton $\{a\}$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The axioms of a monad are formally similar to the monoid axioms.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] In fact, monads are a type of monoid object; they are precisely the monoids among endofunctors $\operatorname {End} (C)$ , with the multiplication given by composition of endofunctors.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Composition of monads is not, in general, a monad.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] For example, the double power set functor ${\mathcal {P}}\circ {\mathcal {P}}$ does not admit any monad structure.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The categorical dual definition is a formal definition of a *comonad* (or *cotriple*); this can be said quickly in the terms that a comonad for a category C is a monad for the opposite category $C^{\mathrm {op} }$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] It is therefore a functor U from C to itself, with a set of axioms for *counit* and *comultiplication* that come from reversing the arrows everywhere in the definition just given.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Monads are to monoids as comonads are to *comonoids*.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Every set is a comonoid in a unique way, so comonoids are less familiar in abstract algebra than monoids; however, comonoids in the category of vector spaces with its usual tensor product are important and widely studied under the name of coalgebras.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The notion of monad was invented by Roger Godement in 1958 under the name "standard construction".
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Monad has been called "dual standard construction", "triple", "monoid" and "triad".
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The term "monad" is used at latest 1967, by Jean Bénabou.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The identity functor on a category C is a monad.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Its multiplication and unit are the identity function on the objects of C .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] In fact, **any monad can be found as an explicit adjunction of functors** using the Eilenberg–Moore category $C^{T}$ (the category of T -algebras).
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] where both functors are given by sending a vector space *V* to its dual vector space $V^{*}:=\operatorname {Hom} (V,k)$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The associated monad sends a vector space *V* to its double dual $V^{**}$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] This monad is discussed, in much greater generality, by Kock (1970).
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] For categories arising from partially ordered sets $(P,\leq )$ (with a single morphism from x to y if and only if $x\leq y$ ), then the formalism becomes much simpler: adjoint pairs are Galois connections and monads are closure operators.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] For example, let G be the forgetful functor from the category **Grp** of groups to the category **Set** of sets, and let F be the free group functor from the category of sets to the category of groups.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] In this case, the associated monad $T=G\circ F$ takes a set X and returns the underlying set of the free group $\mathrm {Free} (X)$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] including any set X into the set $\mathrm {Free} (X)$ in the natural way, as strings of length 1.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] made out of a natural concatenation or 'flattening' of 'strings of strings'.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] This amounts to two natural transformations.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The preceding example about free groups can be generalized to any type of algebra in the sense of a variety of algebras in universal algebra.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Thus, every such type of algebra gives rise to a monad on the category of sets.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Importantly, the algebra type can be recovered from the monad (as the category of Eilenberg–Moore algebras), so monads can also be seen as generalizing varieties of universal algebras.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Another monad arising from an adjunction is when T is the endofunctor on the category of vector spaces which maps a vector space V to its tensor algebra $T(V)$ , and which maps linear maps to their tensor product.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] We then have a natural transformation corresponding to the embedding of V into its tensor algebra, and a natural transformation corresponding to the map from $T(T(V))$ to $T(V)$ obtained by simply expanding all tensor products.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Under mild conditions, functors not admitting a left adjoint also give rise to a monad, the so-called codensity monad.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Its codensity monad is the monad on sets sending any set *X* to the set of ultrafilters on *X*.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] This and similar examples are discussed in Leinster (2013).
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The following monads over the category of sets are used in denotational semantics of imperative programming languages, and analogous constructions are used in functional programming.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The multiplication maps elements of X to themselves, and the two disjoint points in $(X_{*})_{*}$ to the one in $X_{*}$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] In both functional programming and denotational semantics, the maybe monad models partial computations, that is, computations that may fail.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Given a set S , the endofunctor of the **state monad** maps each set X to the set of functions $S\to S\times X$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] In functional programming and denotational semantics, the state monad models stateful computations.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Given a set E , the endofunctor of the **reader** or **environment monad** maps each set X to the set of functions $E\to X$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Thus, the endofunctor of this monad is exactly the hom functor $\mathrm {Hom} (E,-)$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The component of the unit at X maps each element $x\in X$ to the constant function $e\mapsto x$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The multiplication maps a two-variable function $f:E\to (E\to X)$ to its "diagonal component" $(e\mapsto f(e,e)):E\to X$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] In functional programming and denotational semantics, the environment monad models computations with access to some read-only data.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The **list** or **nondeterminism monad** maps a set *X* to the set of finite sequences (i.e., lists) with elements from *X*.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The unit maps an element *x* in *X* to the singleton list [x].
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The multiplication concatenates a list of lists into a single list.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] In functional programming, the list monad is used to model nondeterministic computations.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The covariant powerset monad is also known as the **set monad**, and is also used to model nondeterministic computation.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Given a monad $(T,\eta ,\mu )$ on a category C , it is natural to consider *T -algebras*, i.e., objects of C acted upon by T in a way which is compatible with the unit and multiplication of the monad.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] T -algebras form a category called the *Eilenberg–Moore category* and denoted by $C^{T}$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] For example, for the free group monad discussed above, a T -algebra is a set X together with a map from the free group generated by X towards X subject to associativity and unitality conditions.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Such a structure is equivalent to saying that X is a group itself.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Another example is the ***distribution monad*** ${\mathcal {D}}$ on the category of sets.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] It is defined by sending a set X to the set of functions $f:X\to [0,1]$ with finite support and such that their sum is equal to 1 .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] For example, ${\text{Sym}}^{\bullet }(R^{\oplus n})\cong R[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}]$ where the R -algebra on the right is considered as a module.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Then, an algebra over this monad are commutative R -algebras.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] There is an analogous construction for commutative $\mathbb {S}$ -algebraspg 113 which gives commutative A -algebras for a commutative $\mathbb {S}$ -algebra A .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] If ${\mathcal {M}}_{A}$ is the category of A -modules, then the functor $\mathbb {P$ is the monad given by $\mathbb {P} (M)=\bigvee _{j\geq 0}M^{j}/\Sigma _{j}$ where $M^{j}=M\wedge _{A}\cdots \wedge _{A}M$ j -times.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Then there is an associated category ${\mathcal {C}}_{A}$ of commutative A -algebras from the category of algebras over this monad.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] As was mentioned above, any adjunction gives rise to a monad.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] whose left adjoint sends an object *X* to the free *T*-algebra *T*(*X*).
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Then the above free–forgetful adjunction involving the Eilenberg–Moore category $C^{T}$ is a terminal object in $\mathbf {Adj} (C,T)$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] An initial object is the Kleisli category, which is by definition the full subcategory of $C^{T}$ consisting only of free *T*-algebras, i.e., *T*-algebras of the form $T(x)$ for some object *x* of *C*.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] i.e., *G*(*Y*) can be naturally endowed with a *T*-algebra structure for any *Y* in *D*.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The adjunction is called a **monadic adjunction** if the first functor ${\tilde {G}}$ yields an equivalence of categories between *D* and the Eilenberg–Moore category $C^{T}$ .
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] By extension, a functor $G\colon D\to C$ is said to be **monadic** if it has a left adjoint F forming a monadic adjunction.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] For example, the free–forgetful adjunction between groups and sets is monadic, since algebras over the associated monad are groups, as was mentioned above.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] In general, knowing that an adjunction is monadic allows one to reconstruct objects in *D* out of objects in *C* and the *T*-action.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] For example, the forgetful functor from the category of compact Hausdorff spaces to sets is monadic.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] However the forgetful functor from all topological spaces to sets is not conservative since there are continuous bijective maps (between non-compact or non-Hausdorff spaces) that fail to be homeomorphisms.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Thus, this forgetful functor is not monadic.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The dual version of Beck's theorem, characterizing comonadic adjunctions, is relevant in different fields such as topos theory and topics in algebraic geometry related to descent.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] for a ring homomorphism $A\to B$ between commutative rings.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] This adjunction is comonadic, by Beck's theorem, if and only if *B* is faithfully flat as an *A*-module.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] It thus allows to descend *B*-modules, equipped with a descent datum (i.e., an action of the comonad given by the adjunction) to *A*-modules.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The resulting theory of faithfully flat descent is widely applied in algebraic geometry.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Monads are used in functional programming to express types of sequential computation (sometimes with side-effects).
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] See monads in functional programming, and the more mathematically oriented Wikibook module b:Haskell/Category theory.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Monads are used in the denotational semantics of impure functional and imperative programming languages.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] In categorical logic, an analogy has been drawn between the monad-comonad theory, and modal logic via closure operators, interior algebras, and their relation to models of S4 and intuitionistic logics.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] Monad is also defined in a any weak 2-category, which is defined as a lax 2-functor from terminal category $\mathbb {1}$ to 2-category Cat.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The theory of 2-monads was introduced by Blackwell–Kelly–Power, and 2-monads without prefixes are usually a strict notion.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] A notion that weakens monad laws so that they hold "up to coherent invertible modifications" is called pseudomonad.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] While there are attempts to define monad preserving composition only up to a noninvertible transformation, there is no obvious general notion of lax monad on a weak 2-category, since there is no good 2-category (or even a weak 3-category) of weak 2-categories that contain lax or oplax functors.
[src:category-theory/monad-category-theory] The lax monad was first introduced by Bunge, but other definitions different from lax monad à la Bunge.
[src:category-theory/morphism] In mathematics, a **morphism** is a concept of category theory that generalizes structure-preserving maps such as homomorphism between algebraic structures, functions from a set to another set, and continuous functions between topological spaces.
[src:category-theory/morphism] Although many examples of morphisms are structure-preserving maps, morphisms need not be maps, but they can be composed in a way that is similar to function composition.
[src:category-theory/morphism] Morphisms and objects are constituents of a category.
[src:category-theory/morphism] Morphisms, also called *maps* or *arrows*, relate two objects called the *source* and the *target* of the morphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] There is a partial operation, called *composition*, on the morphisms of a category that is defined if the target of the first morphism equals the source of the second morphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] The composition of morphisms behaves like function composition (associativity of composition when it is defined, and existence of an identity morphism for every object), and the outcome of the composition is a morphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] Morphisms and categories recur in much of contemporary mathematics.
[src:category-theory/morphism] Originally, they were introduced for homological algebra and algebraic topology.
[src:category-theory/morphism] They belong to the foundational tools of Grothendieck's scheme theory, a generalization of algebraic geometry that applies also to algebraic number theory.
[src:category-theory/morphism] A category ${\mathcal {C}}$ consists of two classes, one of *objects* and the other of *morphisms*.
[src:category-theory/morphism] There are two objects that are associated to every morphism, the *source* and the *target*.
[src:category-theory/morphism] A morphism f from X to Y is a morphism with source X and target Y ; it is commonly written as $f:X\to Y$ or $X\xrightarrow {f} Y$ , the latter form being better suited for commutative diagrams.
[src:category-theory/morphism] For many common categories, an object is a set (often with some additional structure) and a morphism is a function from an object to another object.
[src:category-theory/morphism] Therefore, the source and the target of a morphism are often called *domain* and *codomain* respectively.
[src:category-theory/morphism] Morphisms are equipped with a partial binary operation, called *composition* (*partial* because the composition is not necessarily defined over every pair of morphisms of a category).
[src:category-theory/morphism] The composition of two morphisms f and g is defined precisely when the target of f is the source of g , and is denoted $g\circ f$ (or sometimes simply $gf$ ).
[src:category-theory/morphism] The outcome of the composition is a morphism such that the source of $g\circ f$ is the source of f , and the target of $g\circ f$ is the target of g .
[src:category-theory/morphism] For a concrete category (a category in which the objects are sets, possibly with additional structure, and the morphisms are structure-preserving functions), the identity morphism is just the identity function, and composition is just ordinary composition of functions.
[src:category-theory/morphism] The composition of morphisms is often represented by a commutative diagram.
[src:category-theory/morphism] The collection of all morphisms from X to Y is denoted $\mathrm {Hom} _{\mathcal {C}}(X,Y)$ or simply $\mathrm {Hom} (X,Y)$ and called the **hom-set** between X and Y .
[src:category-theory/morphism] The term hom-set is something of a misnomer, as the collection of morphisms is not required to be a set; a category where $\mathrm {Hom} (X,Y)$ is a set for all objects X and Y is called locally small.
[src:category-theory/morphism] Because hom-sets may not be sets, some people prefer to use the term "hom-class".
[src:category-theory/morphism] The domain and codomain are in fact part of the information determining a morphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] For example, in the category of sets, where morphisms are functions, two functions may be identical as sets of ordered pairs, while having different codomains.
[src:category-theory/morphism] The two functions are distinct from the viewpoint of category theory.
[src:category-theory/morphism] Many authors require that the hom-classes $\mathrm {Hom} (X,Y)$ be disjoint.
[src:category-theory/morphism] In practice, this is not a problem because if this disjointness does not hold, it can be assured by appending the domain and codomain to the morphisms (say, as the second and third components of an ordered triple).
[src:category-theory/morphism] A monomorphism can be called a *mono* for short, and we can use *monic* as an adjective.
[src:category-theory/morphism] A morphism f has a **left inverse** or is a **split monomorphism** if there is a morphism $g:Y\to X$ such that $g\circ f=\mathrm {id} _{X}$ .
[src:category-theory/morphism] Thus $f\circ g:Y\to Y$ is idempotent; that is, $(f\circ g)^{2}=f\circ (g\circ f)\circ g=f\circ g$ .
[src:category-theory/morphism] The left inverse g is also called a **retraction** of f .
[src:category-theory/morphism] Morphisms with left inverses are always monomorphisms ( $f_{l}^{-1}\circ f\circ g_{1}=f_{l}^{-1}\circ f\circ g_{2}$ implies $g_{1}=g_{2}$ , where $f_{l}^{-1}$ is the left inverse of f ), but the converse is not true in general; a monomorphism may fail to have a left inverse.
[src:category-theory/morphism] In concrete categories, where morphisms are functions, a morphism that has a left inverse is injective, and a morphism that is injective is a monomorphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] In concrete categories, monomorphisms are often, but not always, injective; thus the condition of being an injection is stronger than that of being a monomorphism, but weaker than that of being a split monomorphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] Dually to monomorphisms, a morphism $f:X\to Y$ is called an epimorphism if $g_{1}\circ f=g_{2}\circ f$ implies $g_{1}=g_{2}$ for all morphisms $g_{1},g_{2}:Y\to Z$ .
[src:category-theory/morphism] An epimorphism can be called an *epi* for short, and we can use *epic* as an adjective.
[src:category-theory/morphism] A morphism f has a **right inverse** or is a **split epimorphism** if there is a morphism $g:Y\to X$ such that $f\circ g=\mathrm {id} _{Y}$ .
[src:category-theory/morphism] The right inverse g is also called a **section** of f .
[src:category-theory/morphism] Morphisms having a right inverse are always epimorphisms ( $g_{1}\circ f\circ f_{r}^{-1}=g_{2}\circ f\circ f_{r}^{-1}$ implies $g_{1}=g_{2}$ where $f_{r}^{-1}$ is the right inverse of f ), but the converse is not true in general, as an epimorphism may fail to have a right inverse.
[src:category-theory/morphism] If a monomorphism f splits with left inverse g , then g is a split epimorphism with right inverse f .
[src:category-theory/morphism] In concrete categories, a function that has a right inverse is surjective.
[src:category-theory/morphism] Thus, in concrete categories, epimorphisms are often, but not always, surjective.
[src:category-theory/morphism] The condition of being a surjection is stronger than that of being an epimorphism, but weaker than that of being a split epimorphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] In the category of sets, the statement that every surjection has a section is equivalent to the axiom of choice.
[src:category-theory/morphism] A morphism that is both an epimorphism and a monomorphism is called a **bimorphism**.
[src:category-theory/morphism] For example, in the category of vector spaces over a fixed field, injective morphisms, monomorphisms and split monomorphisms are the same, as well as surjective morphisms, epimorphisms and split epimorphisms.
[src:category-theory/morphism] In the category of commutative rings, monomorphisms and injective morphisms are the same, while the injection from ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠ into ⁠ $\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠ is an epimorphism that is not surjective; it is neither a split epimorphism nor a split monomorphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] A morphism $f:X\to Y$ is called an isomorphism if there exists a morphism $g:Y\to X$ such that $f\circ g=\mathrm {id} _{Y}$ and $g\circ f=\mathrm {id} _{X}$ .
[src:category-theory/morphism] If a morphism has both left-inverse and right-inverse, then the two inverses are equal, so f is an isomorphism, and g is called simply the **inverse** of f .
[src:category-theory/morphism] Inverse morphisms, if they exist, are unique.
[src:category-theory/morphism] The inverse g is also an isomorphism, with inverse f .
[src:category-theory/morphism] Two objects with an isomorphism between them are said to be isomorphic or equivalent.
[src:category-theory/morphism] While every isomorphism is a bimorphism, a bimorphism is not necessarily an isomorphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] For example, in the category of commutative rings the inclusion $\mathbb {Z} \to \mathbb {Q}$ is a bimorphism that is not an isomorphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] However, any morphism that is both an epimorphism and a *split* monomorphism, or both a monomorphism and a *split* epimorphism, must be an isomorphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] A category, such as a **Set**, in which every bimorphism is an isomorphism is known as a **balanced category**.
[src:category-theory/morphism] A morphism $f:X\to X$ (that is, a morphism with identical source and target) is an endomorphism of X .
[src:category-theory/morphism] A **split endomorphism** is an idempotent endomorphism f if f admits a decomposition $f=h\circ g$ with $g\circ h=\mathrm {id}$ .
[src:category-theory/morphism] In particular, the Karoubi envelope of a category splits every idempotent morphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] An automorphism is a morphism that is both an endomorphism and an isomorphism.
[src:category-theory/morphism] In every category, the automorphisms of an object always form a group, called the automorphism group of the object.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] In category theory, a branch of mathematics, a **natural transformation** provides a way of transforming one functor into another while respecting the internal structure (i.e., the composition of morphisms) of the categories involved.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Hence, a natural transformation can be considered to be a "morphism of functors".
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Informally, the notion of a natural transformation states that a particular map between functors can be done consistently over an entire category.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Indeed, this intuition can be formalized to define so-called functor categories.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Natural transformations are, after categories and functors, one of the most fundamental notions of category theory and consequently appear in the majority of its applications.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] If F and G are functors between the categories ${\mathcal {C}}$ and ${\mathcal {D}}$ (both from ${\mathcal {C}}$ to ${\mathcal {D}}$ ), then a **natural transformation** $\eta$ from F to G is a family of morphisms $(\eta _{X})_{X\in {\text{ob}}({\mathcal {C}})}$ , where $\eta _{X}:F(X)\to G(X)$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] If both F and G are instead contravariant functors, the vertical arrows in the right diagram are reversed.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] If $\eta$ is a natural transformation from F to G , we also write $\eta :F\to G$ or $\eta :F\Rightarrow G$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This is also expressed by saying the family of morphisms $\eta _{X}:F(X)\to G(X)$ is **natural** in X .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] If, for every object X in ${\mathcal {C}}$ , the morphism $\eta _{X}$ is an isomorphism in ${\mathcal {D}}$ , then $\eta$ is said to be a **natural isomorphism** (or sometimes **natural equivalence** or **isomorphism of functors**).
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Two functors F and G are called *naturally isomorphic* or simply *isomorphic* if there exists a natural isomorphism from F to G in their category.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] An **infranatural transformation** $\eta :F\Rightarrow G$ is simply the family of components for all X in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Thus, a natural transformation is a special case of an infranatural transformation for which $\eta _{Y}\circ F(f)=G(f)\circ \eta _{X}$ for every morphism $f:X\to Y$ in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The **naturalizer** of $\eta$ , $\operatorname {nat} (\eta )$ , is the largest subcategory ${\mathcal {C}}_{S}\subseteq {\mathcal {C}}$ (S for subcategory) containing all the objects of ${\mathcal {C}}$ on which $\eta$ restricts to a natural transformation.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Alternatively put, $\operatorname {nat} (\eta )$ is the largest ${\mathcal {C}}_{S}\subseteq {\mathcal {C}}$ such that ${\displaystyle \,\eta |_{{\mathcal {C}}_{S}}\$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] We will now give the precise meaning of this statement as well as its proof.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Consider the category ${\textbf {Grp}}$ of all groups with group homomorphisms as morphisms.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] If $(G,*)$ is a group, we define its opposite group $(G^{\text{op}},{*}^{\text{op}})$ as follows: $G^{\text{op}}$ is the same set as G , and the operation $*^{\text{op}}$ is defined by $a*^{\text{op}}b=b*a$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] All multiplications in $G^{\text{op}}$ are thus "turned around".
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Forming the opposite group becomes a (covariant) functor from ${\textbf {Grp}}$ to ${\textbf {Grp}}$ if we define $f^{\text{op}}=f$ for any group homomorphism $f:G\to H$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] To prove this, we need to provide isomorphisms $\eta _{G}:G\to G^{\text{op}}$ for every group G , such that the above diagram commutes.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This is true since $f^{\text{op}}=f$ and every group homomorphism has the property $(f(a))^{-1}=f(a^{-1})$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Given a group G , we can define its abelianization $G^{\text{ab}}=G/[G,G]$ , where $[G,G]$ denotes the commutator subgroup of G .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Let $\pi _{G}:G\to G^{\text{ab}}$ denote the projection map onto the cosets of $[G,G]$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This homomorphism is "natural in G ", i.e., it defines a natural transformation, which we now check.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] For any homomorphism $f:G\to H$ , we have that $[G,G]$ is contained in the kernel of $\pi _{H}\circ f$ , because any homomorphism into an abelian group kills the commutator subgroup.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This makes ${\text{ab}}:{\textbf {Grp}}\to {\textbf {Grp}}$ a functor and $\pi$ a natural transformation, but not a natural isomorphism, from the identity functor to ${\text{ab}}$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Functors and natural transformations abound in algebraic topology, with the Hurewicz homomorphisms serving as examples.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] from the n -th homotopy group of $(X,x)$ to the n -th homology group of X .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Both $\pi _{n}$ and $H_{n}$ are functors from the category **Top*** of pointed topological spaces to the category **Grp** of groups, and $h_{n}$ is a natural transformation from $\pi _{n}$ to $H_{n}$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Given commutative rings R and S with a ring homomorphism $f:R\to S$ , the respective groups of invertible $n\times n$ matrices ${\text{GL}}_{n}(R)$ and ${\text{GL}}_{n}(S)$ inherit a homomorphism which we denote by ${\text{GL}}_{n}(f)$ , obtained by applying f to each matrix entry.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Similarly, f restricts to a group homomorphism $f^{*}:R^{*}\to S^{*}$ , where $R^{*}$ denotes the group of units of R .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] In fact, ${\text{GL}}_{n}$ and * are functors from the category of commutative rings ${\textbf {CRing}}$ to ${\textbf {Grp}}$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] which is natural in R : because the determinant is defined by the same formula for every ring, $f^{*}\circ {\text{det}}_{R}={\text{det}}_{S}\circ {\text{GL}}_{n}(f)$ holds.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This makes the determinant a natural transformation from ${\text{GL}}_{n}$ to * .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] If K is a field, then for every vector space V over K we have a "natural" injective linear map $V\to V^{**}$ from the vector space into its double dual.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] These maps are "natural" in the following sense: the double dual operation is a functor, and the maps are the components of a natural transformation from the identity functor to the double dual functor.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] For every abelian group G , the set ${\text{Hom}}_{\textbf {Set}}(\mathbb {Z} ,U(G))$ of functions from the integers to the underlying set of G forms an abelian group $V_{\mathbb {Z} }(G)$ under pointwise addition.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The finite difference operator $\Delta _{G}$ taking each function $f:\mathbb {Z} \to U(G)$ to $\Delta (f):n\mapsto f(n+1)-f(n)$ is a map from $V_{\mathbb {Z} }(G)$ to itself, and the collection $\Delta$ of such maps gives a natural transformation $\Delta :V_{\mathbb {Z} }\to V_{\mathbb {Z} }$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Let $\varphi :M\longrightarrow M^{\prime }$ be an R -module homomorphism of right modules.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] For every left module N there is a natural map $\varphi \otimes N:M\otimes _{R}N\longrightarrow M^{\prime }\otimes _{R}N$ , form a natural transformation $\eta :M\otimes _{R}-\implies M'\otimes _{R}-$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] For every right module N there is a natural map $\eta _{N}:{\text{Hom}}_{R}(M',N)\longrightarrow {\text{Hom}}_{R}(M,N)$ defined by $\eta _{N}(f)=f\varphi$ , form a natural transformation ${\displaystyle \eta$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Consider the category ${\textbf {Ab}}$ of abelian groups and group homomorphisms.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] These isomorphisms are "natural" in the sense that they define a natural transformation between the two involved functors ${\textbf {Ab}}^{\text{op}}\times {\textbf {Ab}}^{\text{op}}\times {\textbf {Ab}}\to {\textbf {Ab}}$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This is formally the tensor-hom adjunction, and is an archetypal example of a pair of adjoint functors.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Natural transformations arise frequently in conjunction with adjoint functors, and indeed, adjoint functors are defined by a certain natural isomorphism.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Additionally, every pair of adjoint functors comes equipped with two natural transformations (generally not isomorphisms) called the *unit* and *counit*.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The notion of a natural transformation is categorical, and states (informally) that a particular map between functors can be done consistently over an entire category.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Conversely, a particular map between particular objects may be called an **unnatural isomorphism** (or "an isomorphism that is not natural") if the map cannot be extended to a natural transformation on the entire category.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The maps of the category play a crucial role – any infranatural transform is natural if the only maps are the identity map, for instance.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Some authors distinguish notationally, using $\cong$ for a natural isomorphism and $\approx$ for an unnatural isomorphism, reserving = for equality (usually equality of maps).
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Every finite-dimensional vector space is isomorphic to its dual space, but there may be many different isomorphisms between the two spaces.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] There is in general no natural isomorphism between a finite-dimensional vector space and its dual space.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] However, related categories (with additional structure and restrictions on the maps) do have a natural isomorphism, as described below.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The dual space of a finite-dimensional vector space is again a finite-dimensional vector space of the same dimension, and these are thus isomorphic, since dimension is the only invariant of finite-dimensional vector spaces over a given field.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] However, in the absence of additional constraints (such as a requirement that maps preserve the chosen basis), the map from a space to its dual is not unique, and thus such an isomorphism requires a choice, and is "not natural".
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Intuitively this is because it required a choice, rigorously because *any* such choice of isomorphisms will not commute with, say, the zero map; see (Mac Lane & Birkhoff 1999, §VI.4) for detailed discussion.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Starting from finite-dimensional vector spaces (as objects) and the identity and dual functors, one can define a natural isomorphism, but this requires first adding additional structure, then restricting the maps from "all linear maps" to "linear maps that respect this structure".
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Explicitly, for each vector space, require that it comes with the data of an isomorphism to its dual, $\eta _{V}\colon V\to V^{*}$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] In other words, take as objects vector spaces with a nondegenerate bilinear form $b_{V}\colon V\times V\to K$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This defines an infranatural isomorphism (isomorphism for each object).
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] One then restricts the maps to only those maps $T\colon V\to U$ that commute with the isomorphisms: $T^{*}(\eta _{U}(T(v)))=\eta _{V}(v)$ or in other words, preserve the bilinear form: $b_{U}(T(v),T(w))=b_{V}(v,w)$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Viewed in this light, this construction (add transforms for each object, restrict maps to commute with these) is completely general, and does not depend on any particular properties of vector spaces.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] In this category (finite-dimensional vector spaces with a nondegenerate bilinear form, maps linear transforms that respect the bilinear form), the dual of a map between vector spaces can be identified as a transpose.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] If $\eta :F\Rightarrow G$ and $\epsilon :G\Rightarrow H$ are natural transformations between functors $F,G,H:C\to D$ , then we can compose them to get a natural transformation $\epsilon \circ \eta :F\Rightarrow H$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This vertical composition of natural transformations is associative and has an identity, and allows one to consider the collection of all functors $C\to D$ itself as a category (see below under Functor categories).
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The identity natural transformation $\mathrm {id} _{F}$ on functor F has components $(\mathrm {id} _{F})_{X}=\mathrm {id} _{F(X)}$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This horizontal composition of natural transformations is also associative with identity.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This identity is the identity natural transformation on the identity functor, i.e., the natural transformation that associate to each object its identity morphism: for object X in category C , $(\mathrm {id} _{\mathrm {id} _{C}})_{X}=\mathrm {id} _{\mathrm {id} _{C}(X)}=\mathrm {id} _{X}$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] As identity functors $\mathrm {id} _{C}$ and $\mathrm {id} _{D}$ are functors, the identity for horizontal composition is also the identity for vertical composition, but not vice versa.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Whiskering is an external binary operation between a functor and a natural transformation.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Note that $\mathrm {id} _{H}$ (resp. $\mathrm {id} _{K}$ ) is generally not the left (resp. right) identity of horizontal composition * ( $H\eta \neq \eta$ and $\eta K\neq \eta$ in general), except if H (resp.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] K ) is the identity functor of the category D (resp.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] If C is any category and I is a small category, we can form the functor category $C^{I}$ having as objects all functors from I to C and as morphisms the natural transformations between those functors.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This forms a category since for any functor F there is an identity natural transformation $1_{F}:F\to F$ (which assigns to every object X the identity morphism on $F(X)$ ) and the composition of two natural transformations (the "vertical composition" above) is again a natural transformation.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The isomorphisms in $C^{I}$ are precisely the natural isomorphisms.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] That is, a natural transformation $\eta :F\to G$ is a natural isomorphism if and only if there exists a natural transformation $\epsilon :G\to F$ such that $\eta \epsilon =1_{G}$ and $\epsilon \eta =1_{F}$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The functor category $C^{I}$ is especially useful if I arises from a directed graph.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The horizontal and vertical compositions are the compositions between natural transformations described previously.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] A functor category $C^{I}$ is then simply a hom-category in this category (smallness issues aside).
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Every limit and colimit provides an example for a simple natural transformation, as a cone amounts to a natural transformation with the diagonal functor as domain.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Indeed, if limits and colimits are defined directly in terms of their universal property, they are universal morphisms in a functor category.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] If X is an object of a locally small category C , then the assignment $Y\mapsto {\text{Hom}}_{C}(X,Y)$ defines a covariant functor $F_{X}:C\to {\textbf {Set}}$ .
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] This functor is called *representable* (more generally, a representable functor is any functor naturally isomorphic to this functor for an appropriate choice of X ).
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The natural transformations from a representable functor to an arbitrary functor $F:C\to {\textbf {Set}}$ are completely known and easy to describe; this is the content of the Yoneda lemma.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The reason for Mac Lane's comment is that the study of functors is itself not complete without the study of natural transformations.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] The context of Mac Lane's remark was the axiomatic theory of homology.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] Different ways of constructing homology could be shown to coincide: for example in the case of a simplicial complex the groups defined directly (simplicial homology) would be isomorphic to those of the singular theory.
[src:category-theory/natural-transformation] What cannot easily be expressed without the language of natural transformations is how homology groups are compatible with morphisms between objects, and how two equivalent homology theories not only have the same homology groups, but also the same morphisms between those groups.
